PiperOrigin-RevId: 395251678
Change-Id: I42c37110919dee919f303f2bd818066617468e36","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/861eefd9e575f7a990002058cff9899aa078fcbe"},{"sha":"469a051e0ebe21d647905390111a7ca593a2a906","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Skip get-tuple-element nodes in graphviz.

Re-land cl/394286090, which was rolled back in cl/394760138 due to
CHECK-failures.

The only difference between this and the original is inside GetNodeForEdge.  In
the original, we unnested fusions first, then unnested GTEs.  Now we reverse
the order; first we unnest GTEs, then we unnest fusions.  This is necessary to
avoid crashes when rendering multi-output-fusions.

The tuple index is written inside the consuming instruction as e.g.  "operand 1
= tuple-element 3 of fusion.42".

Alternative considered: My first attempt was to put the tuple element in the
edge label, which right now contains the operand index.  This didn't work well.
Graphviz doesn't prevent the edge label from overlapping with the edge itself
or anything else in the graph.  It was irredeemably messy.

Signed-off-by: Jakub Dyszkiewicz <jakub.dyszkiewicz@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/e83c730b155a6d8de8d6ccc5b5493f71bee690cf"},{"sha":"fa4f1bdb04f1e94f6b55186d84ee43c511c5c203","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kds): Avoid calling `Send()` from different goroutines (#2573)

Rewrote most of KDS mux as it wasn't working as intended.
KDS mux now ensures:

Recv() on underlying streams are always called in the same goroutine
Send() on underlying streams are always called in the same goroutine
Close() actually waits for some goroutine to terminate
Also added extra tests to ensure these invariants

Fixes #2492

Signed-off-by: Jakub Dyszkiewicz <jakub.dyszkiewicz@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/c77077d75dfd651b586da2accd9bc30f81c7ad14"},{"sha":"d5af0df5ec5551fd40bdc5309827dce0d6e20588","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"feat(kuma-cp) initial gateway TrafficRoute support (#2547)

Add support for binding TrafficRoute resources to Gateways. This is
based on outbound proxy generator code, but there are still a number of
missing features and outstanding TODO items.

It is possible to configure simple HTTP Gateway use cases and forward
traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/d5af0df5ec5551fd40bdc5309827dce0d6e20588"},{"sha":"6f2b6210e8ef9fcbe916c73e0950890d161316db","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) remove circular dependency on the Istio submodule (#2742)

The Istio submodule imports Kuma config definitions, and Kuma calls
functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by
moving the config definitions into the Istio submodule, even though
they more properly belong in Kuma itself.

This makes it possible to run `go mod tidy` in the Istio submodule.

This fixes #2087.

* fix(dns): Ensure outbounds are set when migrating from old to new

There's a bug when migrating from one version to the other.
This is caused by the fact that we don't set OutboundEntry when
migrating from old to new format.

This patch:

- Adds validation on VirtualOutboundView to avoid this in the future
- Adds an OutboundEntry for Services with a single tag
- Adds an OutboundEntry for ExternalServices by fetching back the original
virtual service to retrieve its serviceName

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly.molter@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/203c0725665b5b6f1f7edbf31a8c57e291eff25b"},{"sha":"15df736ff07cf044c89baec485b410d6dc2961fc","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(proxy-template): Correct bad merging of duration (#2700)

We used to merge 10s and 0.5s into 10.5s this is because
proto.Duration is made of 2 fields (seconds and nanos) and the default
merge method would just add these 2 fields separately.

This patch copies the content of proto.Merge but enables us
to override the merge policy for specific types.

[{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

[{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.

traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

[{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.
